      {
        "paragraph_index": 3,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe Pb²⁺–Cl⁻ system has been studied for nearly a century because lead(II) forms a series of chloro-complexes (PbCl⁺, PbCl₂(aq), PbCl₃⁻) that are highly relevant to **seawater speciation**, **hydrometallurgy**, and **environmental geochemistry**. The log K₁ ≈ 1.07 at I = 0.1 M is modest, reflecting weak outer-sphere character typical of Pb²⁺ with halides. The large number of independent citations (67!) reflects decades of interest from electrochemists, geochemists, and environmental scientists alike — a testament to lead's environmental significance.\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 21,
            "text": "### Chemistry Insight",
